  "slug": "lamb-tagine-with-apricots",
  "title": "Lamb tagine with apricots",
  "subtitle": "Slow-braised lamb with dried apricots, almond, and ras el hanout.",
  "excerpt": "Lamb shoulder slow-braised with onion, ras el hanout, and a generous handful of dried apricots and toasted almond. The classic Moroccan sweet-savoury tagine, eaten with couscous and a fresh herb salad.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The Moroccan sweet-tagine tradition documented in regional cookery from Fez, Marrakech, and the Sous Valley. The dried-fruit-with-meat technique descends from the Andalusian and Berber kitchens.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A tagine is both a vessel and a dish. The conical lid traps the steam and condenses it back over the meat, producing a tender braise from very little added liquid. A heavy lidded casserole works as well. The dish is the slow conversation between lamb shoulder, ras el hanout, sweet dried apricot, and a final scattering of toasted almond.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The apricots cook to a glossy, soft texture that almost melts into the gravy. Use unsulphured dried apricots if you can find them; the supermarket bright-orange ones are over-treated and turn the dish a similar shade.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
