      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A heavy lidded Dutch oven or a proper Moroccan tagine, both around 4 to 5 litres. The flat hob underneath the tagine needs a diffuser plate to spread the heat.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the lamb",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pat {{lamb-shoulder}} of lamb dry. Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in the Dutch oven over medium-high. Brown the lamb in 3 batches, 3 minutes a side, lifting each batch onto a plate. Don't crowd the pan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drop the heat to medium. Add {{onion}} of chopped onion. Cook 10 minutes until soft and golden. Stir in {{garlic}} of garlic, {{ginger-root}} of ginger, and {{ras-el-hanout}} of ras el hanout for 1 minute. Drop in the {{cinnamon-stick}} of cinnamon stick. Pour in {{tinned-tomatoes}} of chopped tomatoes and cook 3 minutes, mashing with a wooden spoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Slow braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Return the lamb to the pot with any juices. Pour in {{stock-chicken}} of stock and the saffron water. Stir in {{honey}} of honey, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{black-pepper}} of pepper. Bring to a simmer. Cover, drop the heat to its lowest, and cook for 90 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lift the lid. Add {{dried-apricots}} of dried apricots. Cook uncovered for another 30 minutes until the lamb is fully tender and the sauce has reduced to a thick gravy that coats the meat. Stir occasionally to keep the bottom from catching.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Toast the almonds",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "While the tagine finishes, set a small dry frying pan over medium heat. Tip in {{almonds-flaked}} of flaked almonds and toast for 3 minutes, shaking the pan, until pale gold. Tip onto a plate at once or they will continue cooking on the hot metal.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finish and serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest the tagine 15 minutes off the heat. Lift out the cinnamon stick. Taste; the sauce should sit between savoury and softly sweet. Scatter with the toasted almonds, {{coriander}} of chopped coriander, and {{parsley-flat}} of chopped parsley. Serve with couscous, flatbread, or a herb-and-onion salad.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Uncover for the last 30 minutes so the sauce reduces. The dish should sit thick on the spoon.",
              "cause": "Lid kept on for the apricot stage.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin at the end"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use the lowest possible simmer for the 90 minutes covered. The bubble should be barely perceptible. A heat-diffuser helps.",
              "cause": "Heat too high during the braise.",
              "symptom": "Lamb stringy and dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use unsulphured apricots; supermarket bright-orange ones are over-treated and oversweet. Adjust honey to taste; a squeeze of lemon at the end balances.",
              "cause": "Too much honey, or apricots too dominant.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too sweet"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a fresh blend from a deli or Middle Eastern grocer. Stir into the hot onion-ginger mix for a full minute before liquid goes in.",
              "cause": "Old spice blend, or not bloomed in fat.",
              "symptom": "Ras el hanout tasting dusty"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lamb tagine with apricots is a celebration dish from Fez and Marrakech, served at Eid and at weddings, the kind of tagine that takes the proud cook a full afternoon. The sweet-savoury combination comes from the Andalusian-Berber kitchen brought across the strait centuries ago. Serve with mint tea after, never wine.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
